<script lang="ts">
	import MaterialsList from './components/MaterialsList.svelte';
	import DiscussionPrompts from './components/DiscussionPrompts.svelte';
	import ClosingActivity from './components/ClosingActivity.svelte';
	import PersonalConnection from './components/PersonalConnection.svelte';
	import CustomSection from './components/CustomSection.svelte';
	import { getSdgColor } from '$lib/utils/sdg-colors';

	interface Props {
		sdgColor?: string;
	}

	let { sdgColor = getSdgColor(17) }: Props = $props();
</script>

<div class="lesson-content">

	<MaterialsList materials={[{"name":"Images or prints of artwork depicting themes of consumption, waste, sustainability, and production.","isOptional":false},{"name":"Large paper or poster board for each student/group.","isOptional":true},{"name":"Variety of art supplies","isOptional":true}]} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"(10-30 MINUTES) (GRADES 5-12)"} content={"<strong>Art Examples<br><a href=\"https://www.britannica.com/topic/flag-of-the-united-Nations\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Flag of the United Nations</a></strong>, designed by a team led by Oliver Lundquist<br><a href=\"https://www.yvettemattern.com/index\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Global Rainbow</a> by Yvette Mattern. Light Installations projecting rainbow arcs across cities, symbolizing hope and connection across geographical boundaries.<br><a href=\"http://nonviolence.com/about/the-knotted-gun/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Knotted Gun</a>, Non-Violence Project. This iconic sculpture, often found in public spaces globally, features a revolver with its barrel tied in a knot. It directly symbolizes the partnership for peace and non-violence, a crucial element for sustainable development and strong institutions, which are prerequisites for effective partnerships.<br><a href=\"https://www.un.org/en/visitor-centre-new-york/peace-window-marc-chagall\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Peace Window</a> by Marc Chagall This work symbolizes the global partnership for peace, a foundational element of Goal 17, as it represents the collective aspiration for a unified world that enables cooperation on sustainable development.<br><a href=\"https://www.masterworksfineart.com/artists/fernand-leger/lithograph/les-constructeurs-the-builders-1955-2/id/W-6968?srsltid=AfmBOor69n69MJUqmrcjWBR9dbfC3P7fDZyYyFgyaCyjgki-aCXVVeOR\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Les Constructeurs (The Builders)</a> by Fernand Léger This large mural in the UN General Assembly Hall celebrates collective human effort and cooperation in building a better future.<br><a href=\"https://www.un.org/ungifts/war-and-peace-peace\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">War and Peace</a> by Candido Portinari Two monumental panels located in the Delegates’ Lounge at UN HQ, these works depict the horrors of war and the aspirations for peace. The underlying message about the need for global harmony and cooperation to avoid conflict strongly resonates with the spirit of partnership in Goal 17.<br><a href=\"https://prints.nrm.org/detail/261060/rockwell-golden-rule-1961?srsltid=AfmBOoqIGGgJQ0bsDmlcIXcvSdo5IMZlGEaahQ9pkLyte9MgChvyv_nY\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Golden Rule</a> by Norman Rockwell This painting, also located at the UN, depicts people of different races and religions gathered together, emphasizing the principle of treating others as you would like to be treated. It aligns with the inclusive and collaborative nature of partnerships for sustainable development promoted by Goal 17."} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Viewing"} content={"<p>Allow students about 5 minutes to engage with the chosen piece(s), giving the class more or less preamble/guidance about the artwork depending on their needs.<br>Provide a brief introduction to the artwork(s), including any background and/or context that might be important.<br>Adjust the level of guidance based on the students’ age and/or pror knowledge of art.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"Discussion"} content={"<ul>\n<li>What emotions does this artwork evoke in you?</li>\n<li>What aspects of collaboration of interconnectedness does the artwork highlight?</li>\n<li>What messages or stories do you think the artists are trying to convey about working together globally?</li>\n<li>How do these artworks relate to the goals of Global Goal 17: Partnerships for the Goals?</li>\n<li>Can you identify any specific part of the artwork that resonates with a particular aspect of Global Goal 17 (e.g., different entities working together, shared resources, global reach)? How so?</li>\n<li>How does the artwork illustrate the importance of diverse groups coming together?</li>\n<li>What symbols or visual elements stand out to you and what might they represent in the context of global partnerships?</li>\n</ul><br>Emphasize how art can be a powerful tool for expressing ideas, fostering understanding, and inspiring action around global collaboration."} {sdgColor} />

	<PersonalConnection content={"<p>Ask students to reflect on their own experiences with the partnerships and working together towards a common goal. Ask questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>Think about a time you worked with a group of people to achieve something. What made the collaboration successful or challenging?</li>\n<li>Have you ever been part of a team or club where different people brought different skills and perspectives? How did that contribute to the group’s success?</li>\n<li>What are some global issues that you think require different countries and organizations to work together?</li>\n<li>What role do you think young people can play in building partnerships for sustainable development?</li>\n<li>What are some examples of partnerships you see in your school or community?</li>\n</ul><br>Encourage students to share their personal stories and connect them to themes explored in the artwork.</p>"} {sdgColor} />

	<ClosingActivity title={"Closing Activity Options"} content={"<ul>\n<li><strong>One Word Summary:</strong> Ask each student to think of one work encapsulating their biggest takeaway or feeling about global partnerships after this art exploration. Have them share their word with the class, briefly explaining their choice. Bonus: Collect all the words to make a word cloud.</li>\n<li><strong>Quote Connection:</strong> Share an inspiring quote about collaboration or global unity. Facilitate an open discussion about how this quote connects tot he artwork and activity they experienced in class. <em>Example:</em> “Alone we can do so little; together we can do so much.” - Helen Keller “The strength of the team is each individual member. The strength of each member is the team.” - Phil Jackson</li>\n<li><strong>Artwork Challenge:</strong> Divide students into small groups and challenge them to create a “flash partnership art” project in 10 minutes using only the materials available in the classroom. Encourage them to visually represent the idea of different entities working together towards a shared goal.</li>\n<li><strong>Global Goal Gallery:</strong> Have students work in groups to find other artwork that represents different aspects of Global Goal 17 and resonates with them.</li>\n<li><strong>Symbol Design:</strong> Have students design a symbol that represents global partnership and explain its meaning.</li>\n<li><strong>Collaborative Drawing:</strong> Have the whole class contribute to one large drawing, each student adding a section that connects to or builds upon the previous contribution, symbolizing the power of working together.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

	<CustomSection title={"ART EXPLORATION"} content={"<strong>(10-30 MINUTES) (GRADES 5-12)</strong><br><strong>Art Examples<br><a href=\"https://www.britannica.com/topic/flag-of-the-united-Nations\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Flag of the United Nations</a></strong>, designed by a team led by Oliver Lundquist<br><a href=\"https://www.yvettemattern.com/index\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Global Rainbow</a> by Yvette Mattern. Light Installations projecting rainbow arcs across cities, symbolizing hope and connection across geographical boundaries.<br><a href=\"http://nonviolence.com/about/the-knotted-gun/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Knotted Gun</a>, Non-Violence Project. This iconic sculpture, often found in public spaces globally, features a revolver with its barrel tied in a knot. It directly symbolizes the partnership for peace and non-violence, a crucial element for sustainable development and strong institutions, which are prerequisites for effective partnerships.<br><a href=\"https://www.un.org/en/visitor-centre-new-york/peace-window-marc-chagall\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Peace Window</a> by Marc Chagall This work symbolizes the global partnership for peace, a foundational element of Goal 17, as it represents the collective aspiration for a unified world that enables cooperation on sustainable development.<br><a href=\"https://www.masterworksfineart.com/artists/fernand-leger/lithograph/les-constructeurs-the-builders-1955-2/id/W-6968?srsltid=AfmBOor69n69MJUqmrcjWBR9dbfC3P7fDZyYyFgyaCyjgki-aCXVVeOR\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Les Constructeurs (The Builders)</a> by Fernand Léger This large mural in the UN General Assembly Hall celebrates collective human effort and cooperation in building a better future.<br><a href=\"https://www.un.org/ungifts/war-and-peace-peace\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">War and Peace</a> by Candido Portinari Two monumental panels located in the Delegates’ Lounge at UN HQ, these works depict the horrors of war and the aspirations for peace. The underlying message about the need for global harmony and cooperation to avoid conflict strongly resonates with the spirit of partnership in Goal 17.<br><a href=\"https://prints.nrm.org/detail/261060/rockwell-golden-rule-1961?srsltid=AfmBOoqIGGgJQ0bsDmlcIXcvSdo5IMZlGEaahQ9pkLyte9MgChvyv_nY\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Golden Rule</a> by Norman Rockwell This painting, also located at the UN, depicts people of different races and religions gathered together, emphasizing the principle of treating others as you would like to be treated. It aligns with the inclusive and collaborative nature of partnerships for sustainable development promoted by Goal 17.<br><strong>Viewing</strong><br>Allow students about 5 minutes to engage with the chosen piece(s), giving the class more or less preamble/guidance about the artwork depending on their needs.<br>Provide a brief introduction to the artwork(s), including any background and/or context that might be important.<br>Adjust the level of guidance based on the students’ age and/or pror knowledge of art.<br><strong>Discussion</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>What emotions does this artwork evoke in you?</li>\n<li>What aspects of collaboration of interconnectedness does the artwork highlight?</li>\n<li>What messages or stories do you think the artists are trying to convey about working together globally?</li>\n<li>How do these artworks relate to the goals of Global Goal 17: Partnerships for the Goals?</li>\n<li>Can you identify any specific part of the artwork that resonates with a particular aspect of Global Goal 17 (e.g., different entities working together, shared resources, global reach)? How so?</li>\n<li>How does the artwork illustrate the importance of diverse groups coming together?</li>\n<li>What symbols or visual elements stand out to you and what might they represent in the context of global partnerships?</li>\n</ul><br>Emphasize how art can be a powerful tool for expressing ideas, fostering understanding, and inspiring action around global collaboration.<br><strong>Personal Connection</strong><br>Ask students to reflect on their own experiences with the partnerships and working together towards a common goal. Ask questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>Think about a time you worked with a group of people to achieve something. What made the collaboration successful or challenging?</li>\n<li>Have you ever been part of a team or club where different people brought different skills and perspectives? How did that contribute to the group’s success?</li>\n<li>What are some global issues that you think require different countries and organizations to work together?</li>\n<li>What role do you think young people can play in building partnerships for sustainable development?</li>\n<li>What are some examples of partnerships you see in your school or community?</li>\n</ul><br>Encourage students to share their personal stories and connect them to themes explored in the artwork.<br><strong>Closing Activity Options</strong>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>One Word Summary:</strong> Ask each student to think of one work encapsulating their biggest takeaway or feeling about global partnerships after this art exploration. Have them share their word with the class, briefly explaining their choice. Bonus: Collect all the words to make a word cloud.</li>\n<li><strong>Quote Connection:</strong> Share an inspiring quote about collaboration or global unity. Facilitate an open discussion about how this quote connects tot he artwork and activity they experienced in class. <em>Example:</em> “Alone we can do so little; together we can do so much.” - Helen Keller “The strength of the team is each individual member. The strength of each member is the team.” - Phil Jackson</li>\n<li><strong>Artwork Challenge:</strong> Divide students into small groups and challenge them to create a “flash partnership art” project in 10 minutes using only the materials available in the classroom. Encourage them to visually represent the idea of different entities working together towards a shared goal.</li>\n<li><strong>Global Goal Gallery:</strong> Have students work in groups to find other artwork that represents different aspects of Global Goal 17 and resonates with them.</li>\n<li><strong>Symbol Design:</strong> Have students design a symbol that represents global partnership and explain its meaning.</li>\n<li><strong>Collaborative Drawing:</strong> Have the whole class contribute to one large drawing, each student adding a section that connects to or builds upon the previous contribution, symbolizing the power of working together.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

</div>
